Package Import

My aim was to study the associations between several recorded risk factors and the risk of developing cervical cancer, using the patient pool in the risk_factors_cervical_cancer.csv dataset, which was built in order to predict risk factors for cervical cancer. This dataset was collected at Hospital Universitario de Caracas in Caracas, Venezuela, and comprises demographic information, habits, and historic medical records of 858 patients.

# Importing the necessary packages

library(rio)          # Import function for multiple file formats

Data Import

To start the work, the dataset was imported directly from the website and some basic data cleaning was performed. Other target variables and highly correlated variables were removed. The structure of the pre-processed dataset was then explored.

# Immporting the dataset directly from the website
dataset_og <- rio::import(file = "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/00383/risk_factors_cervical_cancer.csv",
                  setclass = "tibble") %>%
  janitor::clean_names()

# Pre-process the dataset
dataset <- dataset_og %>%
  mutate(across(everything(), as.numeric)) %>% #forces "?" to NA
  mutate(across(c(10, 12, 14:25, 29:36), ~ factor(., levels = c(0,1), labels = c("No","Yes")))) %>% #Convert the appropriate columns to factor
  mutate(across(c(1:5, 8, 13, 26:28), as.integer)) %>% #Convert the appropriate columns to integer
  rename_all(.funs = ~ str_replace_all(names(dataset_og),"st_ds","stds")) %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.factor), ~ factor(.x, levels=rev(levels(.x)))))  %>% # so that Yes is considered the positive value in caret
  select(-c(dx:biopsy)) # remove other target variables and highly correlated variables (dx_hpv)

Model development

Several derivation models were built and evaluated through various methods. A seed for reproducibility was set to ensure comparability of results between algorithms, followed by the partition of the data to create a training set dataset (from where we will build our model, where we will train our model) and a validation set validation (new set of data, where we will run our model and assess its performance).

As requested, decision trees were built initially (tree.gini and tree.information).

Model evaluation through various methods

3 model algorithms were built: - Recursive Partitioning and Regression Trees (rpart) - K-nearest Neighbors (knn) - Naive Bayesian Networks (bayes)

Evaluation was performed by analysing the proportion of correctly classified cases, through several methods: - 20% hold-out validation - Multiple 20% hold-out validation (25x) - 10-fold cross validation (3x) - Bootstrap validation

In order to evaluate the models, the ROC metric was used. ROC stands for Receiver Operating Characteristics, and it is a graph of True Positive Rate (sensitivity) vs False Positive Rate (1-Specificity) of the model. It allows the analysis of the impact of these parameters on the error. AUC, which ranges between 0 and 1, is the proportion of the ROC plot that is underneath the curve, and is useful as a single number summary of classifier performance - Higher value = better classifier.

# Tibble with all types of evaluation methods to explore
control_params <- tibble(method = c("LGOCV","LGOCV","repeatedcv","boot_all"),
                         p = c(0.8,0.8,NA,NA),
                         number = c(1,25,10,25),
                         repeats = c(NA,NA,25,NA),
                         desc = c("20% hold-out validation", "Multiple 20% hold-out validation (25x)","3 times 10-fold cross validation", "Bootstrap validation"))

# Iterate over control_params to create a trainControl function

train_controls <- control_params %>%
  pmap(.f = ~ trainControl(method = ..1, p = ..2, number = ..3, repeats = ..4, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary, classProbs=T, savePredictions = T))

# Recursive Partitioning and Regression Trees
set.seed(7)
rpart <- train_controls %>%
  map(.f = ~ train(dx_cancer ~ ., data=prep_dataset, method = "rpart", metric = "ROC", trControl = .x))

# Naive Bayes
set.seed(7)
naive_bayes <- train_controls %>%
  map(.f = ~ train(dx_cancer ~ ., data=prep_dataset, method = "naive_bayes", metric = "ROC", trControl = .x))

# KNN
set.seed(7)
knn <- train_controls %>%
  map(.f = ~ train(dx_cancer ~ ., data=prep_dataset, method = "knn", metric = "ROC", trControl = .x))

names(rpart) <- names(naive_bayes) <- names(knn) <- control_params$desc

# Custom function to plot ROC curves for the 3 selected methods (Decision tree, naive bayes and neural network) in the same plot, for a given validation method
custom_roc_plot <- function(validation_type) {

  #get roc data
  knn_roc <- pROC::roc(knn[[validation_type]]$pred$obs, knn[[validation_type]]$pred$Yes)
  naive_bayes_roc <- pROC::roc(naive_bayes[[validation_type]]$pred$obs, naive_bayes[[validation_type]]$pred$Yes)
  rpart_roc <- pROC::roc(rpart[[validation_type]]$pred$obs, rpart[[validation_type]]$pred$Yes)


  #sensitivities and specificities
  knn_data <- tibble(Sensitivity = knn_roc$sensitivities,
                      Specificity = knn_roc$specificities,
                      Method="knn")
  naive_bayes_data <- tibble(Sensitivity = naive_bayes_roc$sensitivities,
                             Specificity = naive_bayes_roc$specificities,
                             Method="nb")
  rpart_data <- tibble(Sensitivity = rpart_roc$sensitivities,
                       Specificity = rpart_roc$specificities,
                       Method="rpart")

  all_data <- bind_rows(knn_data, naive_bayes_data, rpart_data)

  #AUC
  all_auc <- tibble(names = c("knn","nb","rpart"),
                    values = c(knn_roc$auc,naive_bayes_roc$auc, rpart_roc$auc))

  #Return the plot
  return(
    ggplot() +
      geom_path(data = all_data, aes(y = Sensitivity, x = 1 - Specificity, group=Method, color=Method)) +
      geom_abline(intercept = 0, color="gray") +
      geom_text(aes(x=0.9, y = 0.65, label ="AUC:")) +
      geom_text(data = all_auc, aes(x=rep(0.9,3), y = c(0.45, 0.55, 0.35), color = names, label=scales::number(values))) +
      labs(title = validation_type)
  )
}

# Selected validation methods
control_params$desc %>%
  map(custom_roc_plot)

Predictions are good, as expected - all positive cases are correctly predicted. But once again, the highly unbalanced nature of the dataset and the high correlation of the HPV variable with the target variable must be driving the results. Detection rate is extremely low, also due to low number of cases vs.controls.
